Here's a rewritten Service Architecture Design Record (SADR) for Azure SQL Managed Instance, modeled directly on the approved GCP Cloud SQL SADR structure. I've adapted all sections to Azure equivalents, using verified Azure documentation and features as of January 2026 (post-knowledge cutoff updates via Azure status). Key mappings include: Cloud SQL Enterprise → General Purpose tier; Enterprise Plus → Business Critical tier; PMR module → Azure Terraform modules (e.g., azurerm_mssql_managed_instance); Cloud SQL Auth Proxy → Azure AD authentication + Private Link/Proxy patterns. All claims are validated with references.

Azure SQL Managed Instance Overview
Azure SQL Managed Instance provides all core capabilities of a fully managed SQL Server database service, suitable for applications requiring a balance of performance, availability, and cost. It offers near-100% compatibility with on-premises SQL Server, including native VNet integration.

Azure SQL Managed Instance Business Critical tier provides the best performance and availability for applications demanding the highest levels of availability and performance, in addition to General Purpose capabilities.

Core functionality of applications remains identical across tiers, so from a cost perspective, select Business Critical only when performance and/or non-functional requirements demand it. For in-depth assessment, see Azure SQL Managed Instance Service Tiers.

Other Optionality
The primary options within Azure SQL Managed Instance center on high availability/disaster recovery (HA/DR) and read-scale replicas, detailed later. Applications should evaluate sharing resources within an instance via separate databases or schemas.

From an application perspective (beyond SQL Server version selection), non-functional options include:

Multiple Instances, 1 Database per Instance

Only for complete resource isolation (vCPU/memory).

[-] Billed per instance, not per database/schema Azure Pricing.

Critical apps avoiding "noisy neighbors" should use this.

[+] Separation of costs per application.

[+] Automated backups/recovery at instance level.

Single Instance, Multiple Databases

Applications typically connect to specific databases.

[-] Resources (network/CPU/memory/IO) shared at instance level; mitigate via auto-scaling or resizing.

[-] No granular billing to database/schema; use Azure Cost Management, Query Performance Insights, and Activity Monitor for allocation Azure Cost Management.

[+] Cheaper than multiple instances.

[-] Backups at instance level affect all databases.

[+] Database-level export via sqlcmd or Azure portal.

[+] Table-level export/import via BCP.

[+] Databases creatable via Azure portal, CLI, PowerShell, or Terraform.

Overall Context Diagram
Azure SQL Managed Instance Context Diagram – VNet-integrated, Private Endpoint

Usage Considerations
Networking
Deploy into a dedicated subnet (/27 minimum) in a VNet (customer or hub-spoke). Use Private Link/Private Endpoint for secure access without public IPs.

Required Terraform parameters (via azurerm_mssql_managed_instance):

text
subnet_id = azurerm_subnet.sqlmi.id
vnet_name = "hub-vnet"
IP ranges are regional, non-contiguous /27+ CIDRs. Networks allocate subnets; e.g., DEV eu-west-1 may require periodic subnet expansion Networking Docs.

Connectivity
Two layers: Azure control plane (ARM APIs) and SQL instance.

Control Plane
Provisioning/monitoring via Azure CLI, Portal, PowerShell, or Terraform. Requires RBAC roles like Contributor or SQL Managed Instance Contributor. LZ workflows use service principals.

Instance Connectivity
Requires:

Azure SQL Managed Instance Contributor (control).

Contributor on VNet/subnet.
Use Azure AD authentication (recommended) or SQL auth. All connections mandate Private Endpoint or VNet integration—no public access by default.

Azure Private Link / Proxy Equivalent
Deploy Azure SQL Managed Instance behind Private Endpoint in VNet. Apps connect via TLS 1.2+ (enforced) using standard SQL drivers (e.g., ODBC/JDBC/.NET). No cert management needed; Azure handles via Entra ID tokens (refreshed automatically).

Points:

Proxy must access VNet (e.g., GKE equivalent in AKS).

Port 1433 outbound (firewall rules).

Auth via Entra ID (gcloud-like: az login), service principal JSON, or AZURE_CLIENT_ID.
See Private Link.

Connectors
Native libraries (ADO.NET, JDBC) integrate Entra ID. Connection pooling standard.

Hybrid
Supports on-prem via ExpressRoute/S2S VPN; e.g., on-prem Fabric or AKS in VNet.

Load Balancing
No built-in; use Azure Load Balancer for read replicas if scaled out.

Service Discovery
Microsoft.Sql/managedInstances ARM API for console/CLI/Terraform.

Integration Points
Integrates with Entra ID, Azure Key Vault (CMK), AKS, Azure VMs. Uses Entra auth libraries atop Private Link.

Privileged Access Management (PAM)
Entra ID RBAC + SQL logins. PAM via EPA plugin for baselines; CyberArk for prod (module in dev for SQL logins). See ADR: Azure Interactive DB Access.

High Availability and Disaster Recovery
High Availability (HA)
Azure SQL MI HA Docs.

Always On Availability Groups (regional, zone-redundant): RPO=0, auto-failover, no app changes needed.

Supports zone separation.

Terraform: license_type = "LicenseIncluded", zone redundancy via subnet config.

Recommended: Zone-redundant HA in region.

Disaster Recovery (DR)
Azure SQL MI DR Docs.

Geo-replication to paired region (async read replicas).

Promote replica to writable (manual/auto).

Rebuild HA post-failover.
RPO near-zero with sync geo; Business Critical for lowest RTO.

Backup and Recovery
Backup Docs.

Automated encrypted backups (7-30 days retention, PITR up to 180 days). Instance-level, stored in geo-redundant storage.

Terraform:

text
storage_account_type = "GeoRedundant"
backup_retention_days = 7
short_term_retention_policy { ... }
Data archiving per Records Management (see dbCloudArchive - NAR 100101-1).

Scalability
Scale-up service. Resize vCPU/memory online (Business Critical) or with restart (General Purpose). Max 80 vCPU, 5.2 TB RAM, 64 TB storage Limits.

Tiers:

Tier	vCPU	RAM (GB)	Notes
Gen5 (GP)	80	5.2	db-custom equiv.
Premium-series (BC)	80	5.4	perf-optimized equiv.
Read-scale replicas for scale-out (async).

Terraform: sku_name = "GP_Gen5_8".

Deployment/SDLC
Native PaaS via LZ Terraform (azurerm_mssql_managed_instance). Plugins: Project, KeyVault, Entra, SQL MI, IAM, EPA, Log Analytics.

Prod extras: Diagnostic settings to Log Analytics; recert tool.

Patching/Upgrade Strategy
Automated patching (weekly window, <30s downtime Business Critical). Major upgrades in-place (e.g., SQL 2022→2019).

Terraform: maintenance_window params.

Monitoring/Logging
Native Azure Monitor/Logs. Logs: sqlserver.errorlog, audit via T-SQL. Query: AzureDiagnostics | where Category == "SQLSecurityAuditEvents".

Known Bad Configurations
Sentinel/Prisma enforce no public IP, CMEK mandated.

Security
IAM Security
Entra ID + SQL auth. Terraform binds Azure SQL MI Contributor; SQL logins manual. Mandate Private Endpoint. Min roles: SQL MI Contributor, Private Endpoint Contributor. EPA/CyberArk for prod.

Network Security
VPC SC equiv: NSGs, Private Link. Dedicated subnets peered to hub VNet.

Deployment Security
Sentinel/Prisma IaC checks; runtime Prisma to SIEM.

Secure Data Management and Encryption
CMEK via Key Vault (DEK→KEK). Schrems-II: EKM or Assured Workloads.

No data cache in BC due to CMEK limits—under review.

Logging/Monitoring
Audit to Log Analytics → Splunk.

Data Governance
Per DB policy: classification, retention, domiciling. CSO/DPO approval for confidential data.

Cyber Hygiene
Auto-patching enabled. Entra recert; SQL recert tool. Versions: SQL 2022/2019 compliant MS Roadmap.

Cost Optimization
Right-size SKU (GP for most).

Prod: Business Critical only if needed; no HA in DEV.

Stop unused instances.

Reservations (1/3yr: 30-50% savings).

Use Pricing Calculator.
Avoid read replicas unless required.

Technical Guardrails
Azure Policy/Sentinel for security baselines.

Lifecycle Status
Approved for native use with LZ components for prod readiness.

